body: Responsible, innovative, fashion-forward
title: Text Title

body:
Originating from Denmark in 1990, Jack & Jones is one of Europe’s leading producers of menswear. As experts in denim craftsmanship, quality and design, jeans are the backbone of the Jack & Jones business, but it’s also defined by three unique lifestyles: Originals, Core and Premium.


Jack & Jones Originals’ mission is to provide fun and youthful fast fashion with elements of street culture, while Core is edgy streetwear with hints from the sports universe. Premium is a brand for style seekers, blending minimalism and elegance in its modern high-end tailoring and luxe casuals.


This Learning Moment goes behind the scenes to uncover how Jack & Jones denim is made.

title: JJ_Narrative

body:
Introduced in 2011, Low Impact Denim is an initiative where Jack & Jones works proactively with manufacturers to promote cleaner production methods while maintaining quality standards and trends. Fifty-five million litres of water and 5 million kilowatts of energy was saved in the denim production process in 2014 as a result.


Here are some Low Impact Denim methods used at Jack & Jones.

_items.title: LASER
_items.body: The denim surface is carefully burned with laser beams to fade the fabric, customise wash patterns and create breaks. Laser is waterless and more energy efficient compared to traditional denim treatment and distress techniques.

_items.title: OZONE
_items.body: Ozone is a natural gas that occurs in thunderstorms. It’s used in ozone laundering for its bleaching capabilities, to give denim the stonewashed look without the stones and using less water.

_items.title: RECYCLING
_items.body: Fabric scraps are cut into smaller pieces then shredded into fibres that are reused in weaving a new pair of Low Impact Denim jeans.
